<h2>Tooltip — anchored transient descriptive surface</h2>
<p>The <strong>tooltip</strong> is a small, transient surface that appears on hover or keyboard focus of its trigger and is announced as the trigger's <em>accessible description</em>. It is referenced across the standard already — the <a href="/intents/surface/">Surface Intent</a> lists tooltips at elevation 3–5, and the <a href="/intents/typography/">Typography Intent</a>'s truncation-recovery names a <code>title</code>/tooltip as the way to read a clipped label — but no block delivered one until now. The tooltip <strong>composes existing intents</strong> rather than introducing a new paradigm: it borrows positioning from <a href="/intents/anchor/">Anchor</a>, material from <a href="/intents/surface/">Surface</a>, and the clipped-text case from <a href="/intents/typography/">Typography</a>.</p>

<blockquote>
  <p><strong>A tooltip describes; it does not name.</strong> It is wired with <code>aria-describedby</code> (supplementing the trigger's own accessible name), never <code>aria-label</code> (which would <em>replace</em> the name and lose it whenever the bubble is hidden). It is non-interactive — focus can never live inside it.</p>
</blockquote>

